{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"bae19dde-ed5c-4bb5-a4e5-7affde946ea5","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01Tc3ggKpz6zjyAQn4LDwAZ7","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Diagnosing MAUI Java issue"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01U6M4Vpw9VxFkcjXd6WeRWY","name":"view","arguments":{"path":"/tmp/sv-1e5a5e84233e432fb013f8ac0a378ba0"},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"view the file at /tmp/sv-1e5a5e84233e432fb013f8ac0a378ba0."}],"interactionId":"be03151e-462a-44c1-92b6-3208a487fab3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about common .NET MAUI Android + Java issues:\n\n1. .NET MAUI / Xamarin Android builds require a specific JDK version. Starting with .NET 8, the Android SDK requires JDK 17. But there can be issues with the specific JDK distribution or path.\n\n2. On macOS, the JAVA_HOME path for Adoptium Temurin is typically something like `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`.\n\n\n3. With .NET 8 and later, the Android workload actually ships with its own bundled JDK (Microsoft OpenJDK), and the build system uses `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` which may bypass the JAVA_HOME environment variable entirely. This could be causing a conflict or mismatch.\n\n4. The JDK version itself should be compatible—17.0.12 meets the .NET 8+ requirement—so the issue is likely related to how the build system is locating or using the JDK rather than a version incompatibility.\n\n5. On macOS specifically, if using Adoptium Temurin, the JAVA_HOME path needs to point to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, but even then, the MSBuild property `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` takes precedence over the environment variable. Without knowing the exact error message, I'm thinking through the most common culprits: either a version mismatch causing `UnsupportedClassVersionError`, a path resolution issue with `Could not determine java version`, or something similar.\n\nThe real issue here is likely that .NET 8+ ships with its own bundled Microsoft OpenJDK 17, and there's a conflict between that and the user's system JAVA_HOME. On macOS, the .NET Android SDK looks for the JDK in specific locations, and if the wrong one gets picked up, the build fails. JAVA_HOME` environment variable and let the build use its bundled OpenJDK, or explicitly configure `<JavaSdkDirectory>` in the project file to point to the JDK. On macOS specifically, Temurin's JAVA_HOME path needs to follow the correct format pointing to the JDK's Contents directory.\n\nThe .NET Android workload might not be finding the JDK properly even if JAVA_HOME is set, which commonly happens when the Microsoft OpenJDK wasn't installed as part of the workload setup.\n\nLet me think through the most practical fixes for this scenario and check if there's any relevant context in the repository that might help narrow down the exact issue.","outputTokens":1593,"requestId":"0456:75BF8:B19490:CA7333:6A027A1B"},"id":"69a4a3b5-efd5-44c2-a980-645f257241c4","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:54:21.238Z","parentId":"816a8992-ef20-4a80-b5a0-d1c1ab23dd12"}
