{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"868a0f58-d781-4a42-b6f4-a90a734765be","content":"The most likely cause: **.NET MAUI Android ignores `JAVA_HOME`**. The build system uses the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property, which typically points to the **Microsoft OpenJDK** bundled with the Android workload — not your Temurin JDK.\n\n### Fix options (pick one):\n\n**Option A — Use the bundled Microsoft OpenJDK (recommended):**\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\nThis installs/repairs the Microsoft OpenJDK 17. Remove or unset your `JAVA_HOME` so it doesn't conflict, and the build will find the bundled JDK automatically.\n\n**Option B — Point MSBuild to your Temurin JDK:**\n\nAdd this to your `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup Condition=\"$([MSBuild]::IsOSPlatform('osx'))\">\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\nOr pass it on the command line:\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```\n\n### Why this happens\n\nThe .NET Android SDK discovers Java via an internal search order (`$(JavaSdkDirectory)` → workload-bundled JDK → Visual Studio paths). The `JAVA_HOME` environment variable is **not** in that search order, so having it set and `java -version` working correctly doesn't help the MSBuild-based build.\n\nIf you can share the exact error message, I can narrow it down further.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"be03151e-462a-44c1-92b6-3208a487fab3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The directory is empty. This is a general question, not tied to a specific repo. Let me answer based on my knowledge.\n\nThe most likely issue: **.NET 8+ Android workload ships its own Microsoft OpenJDK 17** and uses it via the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property. It does **not** use the `JAVA_HOME` environment variable by default. \n\nHowever, the user says the build fails with a Java-related error. Without the exact error message, the most common scenarios are:\n\n1. **The bundled Microsoft OpenJDK wasn't installed** (e.g., `dotnet workload install maui` didn't install the JDK component), and the build can't find Java at all.\n\n\n2. **JAVA_HOME is being picked up but there's a path or compatibility issue** with Temurin.\n3. **The user needs to explicitly tell MSBuild to use their JDK** via `<JavaSdkDirectory>`.\n\nThe typical fixes are installing the workload with the bundled JDK, explicitly pointing `<JavaSdkDirectory>` to the Temurin installation in the project file, or clearing JAVA_HOME to let the workload use its own JDK. I should give a more direct answer focused on what's most likely causing the problem.\n\nThe real issue is that .NET MAUI doesn't actually respect JAVA_HOME—it has its own JDK discovery mechanism, so there's probably a conflict between what the user has set and what the build system is trying to use.","outputTokens":850,"requestId":"044B:39DF49:AE91FF:C7884C:6A027A3C"},"id":"7af38f41-30d6-4120-a3a6-5a931b704083","timestamp":"2026-05-12T00:54:38.298Z","parentId":"27b74506-c95a-43d9-b700-b1afec3c35e7"}
